text:
I agree with low tech. word of mouth is perfect. always works.

the accuracy is not a subject of concern here. rather the way it is presented. it NEEDS context. something along the lines of,
"hey Keneni, count 10 people around you whom you really love. tell me their names."
*we count ten people. with names*
"now think about this. tomorrow you will lose person x and person y. now 8 of the people are alive."
"day two and you find out that only 5 are left"
"you realize that in under a week, you don't have any of your lvoed ones with you"
...

I hope you see where I am heading to.

another example. every time apple makes an announcement of their latest product, they never give us numbers or stats, instead they give us information related to the performance of last year's devices:"the new iphone is x% faster than last year's iphone"
we NEED to use an established cultural motif, for lack of a better word. we must come up with a cultural element that we can tie corona virus awareness into.

the numbers alone, accurate or not, are useless.
